/COMMIT_MSG.message: I think the expansion needs to be well defined. iiuc, matrix attributes are recursively merged. what about list attributes, are they replaced or extented?
Maybe it shouldn't be called 'matrix jobs' as this is more of a config meta-programming :)

There is no merging. Those matrix attributes will shadow what's defined on the job itself. But since we are expanding this to distinct jobs during config loading they will behave the same as if defined separately.

E.g. fully expanded the jobs look like:

	- job:
	    name: tox-py37-linux
	    parent: base
	    vars:
	      python_version: python3.7

	- job:
	    name: tox-py37-windows
	    parent: base-windows
	    vars:
	      python_version: python3.7

	- job:
	    name: tox-py38-linux
	    parent: base
	    vars:
	      python_version: python3.8

	- job:
	    name: tox-py38-windows
	    parent: base-windows
	    vars:
	      python_version: python3.8

I think what we need to define is how those 'matrix' attributes will behave in case there is a collision of some sort.

E.g. what happens in case of a job like:

    - job:
	name: {foo,bar}-{x,y}
	matrix:
	  foo:
	    parent: foo
	  bar:
	    parent: bar
	  x:
	    parent: foo
	  y:
	    parent: bar

Maybe that's what you meant?
... and yes, we probably have to merge e.g. the vars so we have the same behavior as with normal job inheritance. Thanks for the input!

Yes, or even:

  - job:
      name: {foo,bar}
      matrix:
        foo:
          vars:
            list: [42]
            nested:
              value: 1
        bar:
          vars:
            list: [43]
            nested:
              other: value

 https://opendev.org/openstack/tripleo-ci/src/commit/e593b89184a2352f602517098625fb71a0a46110/playbooks/tripleo-ci/install-built-repo.yml#L5

Not at all, that's another established code review pattern to carry away things for future follow ups. If an essential thing, like a critical fix to unblock things, needs to be landed first. Just that me considering such a drastic improvement for CI pipelines an essential and critical thing. I may be wrong.
folks, let's please just have this running for all CI jobs, then polish that remains. Thanks!

you are not wrong it is a drastic change and it is critical (we need this because of docker.io rate limiting basically)

maybe because of this we should take the time to get it right? look... all i'm saying is it takes 5 mins for someone to make a minor change from a review comment. So ok it merges this evening instead of this afternoon.

If you disagree with the change then it takes even less, like 1 min to say 'thanks for review, no i won't be doing this, maybe later'

It just felt a bit rude when you said 'nope ignore these guys lets merge this' which is why i felt compelled to say something.

if you keep doing that in (your) reviews, how many reviewers do you think you will have after a while?

in general we need to encourage folks to keep reviewing code. we all need this it is the only way we keep things merging.

o/ bogdando - I appreciate the sentiment and it's great that you are taking the time to review these patches and yes we *are* on a deadline - it all needs to merge this sprint.

I'd be careful however to dismiss other reviewer comments - they may or may not be valid but they should at least be acknowledged.

Otherwise the folks that spent time to review this and comment on it were just wasting their time.

sysinv/sysinv/sysinv/sysinv/api/controll.message: usually a modify operation would come in as a PUT/PATCH
as this is being moved to a db location, additional semantic checks can be performed in the api, prior to the rpc call.
do all hosts need to be unlocked (per commit message) before this is allowed

At any point in time the user is allowed to complete the restore. There is no need to enforce a check for all hosts to be unlocked. Eg: While restoring 5/100 servers have hardware failures, there are no funds to replace all of them.

If the user chooses to complete the restore before all nodes are up, then auto-apply for an app will fail if that app has pods on nodes that are down. The user then have to either delete stuck pods or bring up the remaining nodes, then do a manual app apply.


Apps that may be auto-applied after exiting the restore state must not have any pods on nodes that are down, otherwise an auto-apply may start and fail because of pods stuck on down nodes.
These apps are: HELM_APP_PLATFORM, HELM_APP_OIDC_AUTH, HELM_APP_CERT_MANAGER, HELM_APP_OPENSTACK.

I think pods of apps can be placed on other host than the default through overrides, so we don't know where they are.
Need to double check, assuming the user didn't override the pods locations, with the exception of HELM_APP_OPENSTACK the other 3 apps only spawn pods on master nodes(controllers), thus if openstack app isn't installed the restore can be completed after controllers are unlocked.
if minimum the controllers must be unlocked, should there be a semantic check for the controllers admin state before allowing "complete"?
This doesnt appear to be referenced elsewhere
normally, GET operations do not require this lock.

sysinv/sysinv/sysinv/sysinv/conductor/ma.message: We should save the state to the DB rather than using a flag file.

Is the tsconfig.py::RESTORE_IN_PROGRESS_FLAG being obsoleted?  (its referencing os.path.join(PLATFORM_CONF_PATH, '.restore_in_progress') 

This should be defined as a constant; there's a reference to it also in https://review.opendev.org/#/c/753310/2/sysinv/sysinv/sysinv/sysinv/conductor/manager.py   ...

The flag referenced by tsconfig.py is created by the restore playbook. It is removed during first controller unlock. The lifetime of that flag is from the start of the restore playbook until controller-0 unlock. It has the purpose of gating some operations in that time frame. It is not drbd synced. It has meaning only on controller-0.

The new introduced flag exists from the end of the restore playbook until manually(or automatically in the future) removed.
It has the purpose of not allowing applications to auto-apply during its existence. It is drbd synced. It has meaning for the whole restore. For example during restore controller-0 might have a power loss. Services swact to controller-1 and sysinv knows that a restore procedure is in progress.

/COMMIT_MSG.message: sp: occur

sysinv/sysinv/sysinv/sysinv/conductor/ma.message: with the new proposed restore API, we should get this from the DB rather than a flag file.

Is there any value added if the backend implementation of an on/off switch is moved from a drbd synced flag file to the database?

There is no other information needed other than On/Off.

I'm thinking about this from two perspectives: 1) we have an API driving a system state so it should be persisted in the DB like pretty much everything else and 2) we may need additional states/information saved to support more complex application restore scenarios in the future.

1. test-requirements.txt should be removed from doc build
2. doc/requirements.txt includes all requirements specific to doc generation. This doesn't include these 2 packages actually required by storlets.tools module.
